Anatomy.promo: Tickle your funny bone! Quiz yourself on head and neck anatomy. Topics vary from the smallest minor salivary gland to the bones and muscles of the head and neck region!

q1.text: Which lymph node does the mandibular incisors immediately drain to?
q1.explanation: The mandibular incisors drain directly to the submental lymph nodes, situated between the anterior bellies of the digastric muscle. Following this, lymph fluid is transported to the submandibular lymph nodes followed by the deep cervical lymph nodes, which are situated on the internal jugular vein at the level of the cricoid cartilage.

q2.text: Which lymph nodes do the maxillary incisors immediately drain to?
q2.explanation: The submandibular lymph nodes receive lymphatic drainage from the maxillary structures, the submental nodes, the mandibular posterior teeth and surrounding structures and the tongue and nasal cavity. The parotid gland drains into the preauricular nodes. These both drain into the deep cervical lymph nodes situated on the internal jugular vein at the level of the cricoid cartilage.

q3.text: Which of the following is not part of Waldeyer’s ring?
q3.explanation:
All options are correct except for tonsillar tonsils, which is a fictitious word.

Waldeyer’s ring is an anatomical term collectively describing the annular arrangement of lymphoid tissue in the pharynx. It is made up of 4 tonsil regions:
Tubal tonsils 
Pharyngeal tonsils
Lingual tonsils
Palatine tonsils

q4.text: At 5 years old, the cranium is ___% of its adult longitudinal dimensions.
q4.explanation: Calvarial (skull) bones are pulled away from each other due to the growing brain, causing the formation of bone at the sutures that separate the bones.

q5.text: True or false: At birth, there are areas of the brains that are not protected by bone.
q5.explanation: These unprotected areas of the skull are known as fontanelles, also known as ‘soft spots’. Fontanelles are soft membranous gaps between the cranial bones that make up the skull of the infant. They allow for rapid stretching and deformation of the neurocranium as the brain expands faster than the surrounding bone can grow. There are six fontanelles at birth, which reduce in size and calcify over time after brain growth has completed, forming the sutures of the skull.

q6.text: Which of the following structures forms the skullcap of the brain?
q6.explanation:
The calvaria is made up from the superior portions of the frontal bone, occipital bone, and parietal bones. It forms the upper part of the neurocranium and covers the cranial cavity containing the brain.

The neurocranium is the general structure that forms the protective casing around the brain. It is made up of 8 cranial bones. The calvaria is the anatomical name for the top portion (skullcap) of the neurocranium.

The splanchnocranium is another name for the facial skeleton, which is made up of 14 facial bones.

The chondrocranium is the cartilaginous skeletal structure of the developing fetal skull that grows to envelop the rapidly growing embryonic brain.

The ossicles (also called auditory ossicles) are three bones in either middle ear that are among the smallest bones in the human body. They serve to transmit sounds from the air to the fluid-filled labyrinth (cochlea).

q7.correctAnswer: The bones of the middle ear

otherAnswers.a1: Sharp areas of remnant bone in the post-extraction socket

q7.explanation: The ossicles (also called auditory ossicles) are three bones in either middle ear that are among the smallest bones in the human body. They serve to transmit sounds from the air to the fluid-filled labyrinth (cochlea).

q8.explanation:
The largest fontanelle is the anterior fontanelle, found between the two frontal and parietal bones.

A fontanelle is the part of the infant human skull consisting of soft membranous gaps (known as sutures) between the cranial bones of the calvaria (skullcap). These membranous gaps provide flexibility to the neurocranium, as the brain expands faster than the surrounding bone can grow. In pathology, fusion of the skull bones at birth is known as craniosynostosis.

q9.correctAnswer: Fusion of the skull bones at birth

otherAnswers.a1: Formation of flexible membranes between certain cranial bones
otherAnswers.a2: The dense fibres that form the joints between cranial bones
otherAnswers.a3: Absence of a major portion of the brain skull and scalp that occurs during embryonic development
otherAnswers.a4: A birth defect sometimes caused by the incomplete closure of the neural tube

q9.explanation:
Craniosynostosis is rare skull defect that causes babies to be born with an abnormally shaped head. This is due to fibrious sutures in an infant skull prematurely fusing and turning to bone, preventing normal growth and expansion of the skull. This causes other areas of the skull to grow in compensation to accommodate the growing brain.

If there is not enough compensation of the skull growth to accommodate the growing brain, an increase in intracranial pressure can occur. This can lead to a variety of impairments to vision, sleeping, eating and mental development with a severe reduction in IQ.

This rare condition affects an estimated 1 in every 1,800 to 3,000 children. Three out of every four cases affect boys. 80-95% of cases are non-syndromic, meaning that there are no other birth defects and that the cause is unknown. The remaining percentage accounts for Craniosynostosis being the result of one of several rare syndromes. Some of these include Apert syndrome and Crouzon syndrome.

Formation of flexible membranes between cranial bones describes normal skull development. The dense fibres that form the joints between cranial bones are known as sutures or synarthroses. Absense of a major portion of the brain is known as anencephaly. A birth defect characterised by incomplete closure of the neural tube is known as spina bifida.

Ref: NHS Choices

q10.text: When does the anterior fontanelle close?
q10.explanation: The anterior fontanelle is the last fontanelle to close following birth. It is not completely closed until the middle of the second year of life. Interestingly, full ossification starts in the late twenties and finishes before age 50. The posterior and lateral fontanelles are obliterated by six months in life.

q11.text: Where is the sagittal suture found?

otherAnswers.a3: Between the parietal and occipital bones
otherAnswers.a4: Between the frontal and parietal bones

q11.explanation:
The sagittal suture is found in the sagittal plane of the skull; that is, along the length of the skull between the two parietal bones on the skullcap (calvaria). The lambdoid suture lies between the parietal and occipital bones. The coronal suture lies between between the frontal and parietal bones.

The frontal suture is found between the two frontal bones in infants and children. This suture disappears by eight months in life, whereby the two halves of frontal bone are fused fully together. This suture is also known as the metopic suture, but this is often a term applied to a persistent frontal suture.

No suture exists between the two temporal bones.

q12.text: True or false: At birth, the frontal and parietal bones do not meet.
q12.explanation: At birth, the 2 frontal and 2 parietal bones do not meet. The open interface between these developing bones is known as the anterior fontanelle, which is a soft membranous area. This structure allows for flexibility in the skull, important during parturition. This membranous area is also known as the ‘soft spot’. The anterior fontanelle closes at 12-18 months into life.

q13.text: What is the formal name of the joint that binds teeth to their respective alveolar sockets?
q13.explanation:
Gomphosis is the formal name of the joint between the surface of the tooth (cementum) and the alveolar socket.  In a general sense, a gomphosis is a specialised fibrous joint in which a conical process of one bone fits into the socket of another bone. ‘Gomphos’ is a Greek word for ‘bolt’. No large movement is permitted at these tooth-socket joints, although some physiological movement is possible (0.1mm).

A diarthrosis is a freely moveable joint. All diarthrosis joints are synovial joints. The two terms can be considered interchangeable. Synostosis is the term for the normal or abnormal fusion of two bones by osseous material. It can be normal in the sense of fusion of the epiphysis during puberty.

A suture is the term applied to the fibrous joint between certain cranial bones. The formal term for this joint is known as a synarthrosis.

q14.text: True or false: the fibres in sutures of the skull are also found within areas of the periodontal ligament.
q14.explanation:
Sharpey’s fibres are mainly made up of strong type III collagen fibres. They connect periosteum to bone. Periosteum is the membrane that covers the outer surface of all bones (it is made up of dense irregular connective tissue).

These fibres are found between cranial bones, forming fibrous joints known as synarthroses. Synarthrosis joints are a type of joint that permits little or no movement under normal conditions.

q15.text: Where is the lambdoid suture found?
q15.correctAnswer: Between the parietal and occipital bones

otherAnswers.a2: Between the frontal and parietal bones
otherAnswers.a4: Between the occipital bone and the mastoid portion of the temporal bone

q15.explanation:
The lambdoid suture is a dense fibrous connective tissue joint that connects the parietal and occipital bones. It is continuous with the occipitomastoid suture (suture between the occipital bone and the mastoid portion of the temporal bone).  The lambdoid suture is named as such due to its resemblance to the Greek lowercase lambda letter.

The sagittal suture is found in the sagittal plane of the skull; that is, between the two parietal bones on the skullcap (calvaria). The lambdoid suture lies between the parietal and occipital bones. The coronal suture lies between between the frontal and parietal bones.

The frontal suture is found between the two frontal bones in infants and children. This suture disappears by eight months in life, whereby the two halves of frontal bone are fused fully together. This suture is also known as the metopic suture, but this is often a term applied to a persistent frontal suture.

q16.text: Which suture is most commonly affected by craniosynostosis?
q16.explanation:
Craniosynostosis is defined as the premature fusion of the cranial sutures, leading to abnormal skull growth, shape and development.

The sagittal suture is most commonly affected. This is known as sagittal synostosis, or scaphocephaly, leading to compensatory growth of the skull parallel to the fused suture line. This therefore forces the head to grow long and narrow, rather than wide, as the fused sagittal suture cannot permit an increase in skull width.

q17.text: True or false: Compensatory growth of the skull in an anteroposterior direction is known as dolichocephaly.
q17.explanation:
Early fusion of the cranial sutures, known as craniostenosis, results in compensatory growth of the other sutures. This uneven skull growth leads to abnormal skull shapes. The most common suture to undergo craniostenosis is the sagittal suture. This leads to symmetrical growth in an anteroposterior direction, as the sutures in the anterior and posterior portions of the developing skull have not yet calcified and thus can still permit growth. This condition is known as dolichocephaly, whereby the head is longer than would be expected.

However, if the area of the suture fusion is asymmetric, only affecting one suture on one side of the skull, the deformation is also asymmetric. This condition is known as plagiocephaly, whereby the head can have one of a variety of deformations.

q18.text: Early fusion of one coronal suture will lead to which of the following clinical manifestations?
q18.correctAnswer: Flattening of the forehead on the affected side

otherAnswers.a1: Flattening of the forehead on both left and right sides
otherAnswers.a2: A long and narrow appearance to the skull rather than wide
otherAnswers.a3: A triangular appearance to the scalp
otherAnswers.a4: Flattening of the skull in the back of the skull on the affect side

q18.explanation:
Early fusion of one coronal suture will lead to flattening of the forehead on the affected side.  This condition is known as coronal synostosis, or anterior plagiocephaly. This is because the coronal suture is found between the frontal and parietal bones, at the forehead region. This would prevent normal development in this region whilst the other bones grow, leading to a flat appearance.

Flattening of the forehead on both sides would indicate bicoronal synostosis, whereby both coronal sutures have fused prematurely. A long and narrow appearance to the skull would indicate fusion of the sagittal suture (scaphocephaly). A triangular scalp appearance would indicate premature fusion of the frontal/metopic suture (trigonocephaly). Flattening of the skull to the back side would indicate premature fusion of the lambdoid suture (posterior plagiocephaly).

q19.text: Failure of the cranial base to lengthen leads to:

otherAnswers.a4: A significant class II incisor relationship

q19.explanation: Failure of the cranial base to lengthen leads to a lack of mid-facial growth, as seen in Crouzon’s syndrome. In this syndrome, patients often display with a regressed mid-face and shallow orbits, leading to a prominent eyeball appearance (proptosis). The arrangement of teeth is also affected, requiring specialist orthodontic care.

q20.text: In normal anatomy, approximately how many circumvallate papilla exist on the tongue?
q20.explanation:
Circumvallate papillae are one of four lingual papillae found on the human tongue. They are known as ‘taste buds’ and are associated with taste function. The average human has 250 taste buds.

8-12 circumvallate papillae are arranged in V-shape immediately anterior to the sulcus terminalis, which is the junction between the posterior 1/3 of the tongue and the anterior 2/3 of the tongue.  Each circumvallate papilla is 0.5cm in diameter and exists as a prominent exophytic mass with a circular depression surrounding it, forming a moat. Lingual salivary glands, known as Von Ebner’s glands, empty a serous secretion into these depressions to flush material from the base of the depression. By constantly flushing food particles, the taste buds can respond to the changing stimuli rapidly.

q21.text: The tonsillar lymph node is found at the level of the _____________.
q21.explanation: The tonsillar lymph node is found at the level just below the angle of the mandible. This lymph node forms part of the  anterior cervical lymph node group. It is important to palpate these lymph nodes during a routine dental examination to check for signs of lymphadenopathy. Other lymph nodes in this region include the anterior cervical, posterior cervical, submandibular, submental and supra-clavicular lymph nodes.

q22.text: Which of the following muscles act to depress the mandible?
q22.explanation:
The mylohyoid is a paired muscle of mastication. It originates from the mylohyoid line of the mandible and inserts into the body of the hyoid. It’s innervation is the mylohyoid nerve, which is a branch of the inferior alveolar nerve given from the mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve.

All the other options are involved in elevation of the mandible, and thus closure of the mouth.

q23.text: The superior sagittal sinus immediately empties into the ____________.
q23.explanation:
The superior sagittal sinus is a dural venous sinus, which are venous channels found between layers of dura mater in the brain. They receive venous blood from veins and CSF from the subarachnoid space, to ultimately empty into the internal jugular vein.

The superior sagittal sinus (SSS) empties first into the confluence of sinuses, which is the point of union of the SSS, the straight sinus and the occipital sinus. From the confluence of sinuses, the venous drainage pattern is: confluence of sinuses -> transverse sinuses -> sigmoid sinus -> internal jugular vein.

q24.text: Which of the following structures is 'the junction between the lips and the skin of the face'?
q24.explanation:
The vermillion border is the sharp demarcation between the lip and the adjacent skin of the face. It is named as such due to the vermillion (bright red) colour of the lips. It is also known as the ‘cupid’s bow’, due to its bow-like shape.

The border represents the observed change in the epidermis between the highly keratinised external skin of the face and the less keratinised internal skin, as represented by the lip. The vermillion border is the only part of the oral mucosa which is persistently exposed to the external environment.

q25.correctAnswer: The corner of the mouth forming the junction between the upper and lower lip

otherAnswers.a1: A small fold of tissue that secures the upper lip to the maxilla
otherAnswers.a2: A small fold of tissue that secures the upper lip to the maxilla
otherAnswers.a3: The roof of the mouth with a bony floor
otherAnswers.a4: The portion of free gingiva that fills the area between teeth apical to their contact area

q25.explanation: The labial commissure is the anatomical term for the corner of the mouth that forms the junction between the upper and lower lip. The small fold of tissue describes the labial frenulum. The vertical depression in the middle area of the lip describes the philtrum. The bony roof of the mouth describes the hard palate. The portfolio of free gingiva that fills the area between teeth apical to their contact area describes interdental papilla. Gingival embrasures exist coronal to this area, assuming a contact point exists.

q26.text: According to Nordland and Tarnow, there are four classes of gingival embrasures. Which class described a case where ‘the crest of the interdental papilla is located between the contact point and the most coronal extent of the interproximal cemento-enamel junction (CEJ)‘.

otherAnswers.a4: This definition does not fit any of the classifications

q26.explanation:
Nordland and Tarnow classified the loss of papilla height into 4 classes based on three anatomical landmarks: interdental contact point, facial apical extent of CEJ and the interproximal coronal extent of the CEJ (3) (fig. 1). They are:

> Normal: Interdental papilla fills the gingival embrasure to the apical extent of the interdental contact point/ area.

> Class I : The tip of the interdental papilla is located between the contact point and the most coronal extent of the interproximal cemento-enamel junction (CEJ).

> Class II: The crest of the papilla is at or apical to the interproximal CEJ but coronal to the facial CEJ.

> Class III: Crest of the papilla is at or apical to the facial CEJ.

Ref: Ravishankar, Y., Srinivas, K., Sharma, S.K., Kumar P.S. (2012) “Management Of Black Triangles And Gingival Recession: A Prosthetic Approach”. Indian Journal of Dental Sciences, 4(1), pp. 141-146.

otherAnswers.a2: Has no effect on the cheek
otherAnswers.a3: Is an antagonist to the masseter
otherAnswers.a4: Is innervated by the temporal branch of the facial nerve

q27.explanation:
The buccinator muscle is a thin quadrilateral muscle found between the maxilla and the mandible at the side of the face. It forms the lateral wall of the oral cavity as well as the anterior region of the cheek. It originates from the alveolar processes of the maxilla and mandible and inserts into the fibres of the orbicularis oris. It acts to compress the cheek against the teeth and for blowing.

The antagonist to the masseter is the digastric muscle (anterior and posterior bellies).

The buccal branch of the facial nerve innervates the buccinator muscles. After the facial nerve has passed through the parotid gland, it forms the parotid plexus (the facial nerve does not innervate the parotid gland – it is innervated by CN IX via the otic ganglion) which splits into five branches. These five branches are: temporal, zygomatic, buccal, marginal mandibular and cervical. The mnemonic, ‘Ten Zulus Brought My Cat’, can be used an ‘aide-memoire’ for this.

q28.text: Cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is normally found in the:
q28.explanation:
CSF is a clear fluid found in the brain and the spine. It acts to cushion the brain’s cortex to provide mechanical protection, as well providing immunological benefits. It occupies the subarachnoid space (the space between the arachnoid mater and the pia mater).

CSF is produced in the choroid plexus of the ventricles of the brain. The brain produces roughly 500mL of CSF per day. However, this fluid is constantly absorbed, so there is only 100-160mL of CSF present in the body at any one time.

q29.text: Which of the following is not a paired bone?
q29.explanation:
There are a total of 14 bones in the skull, totalling 22 bones counting pairs. The skull is divided into the bones of the cranium and the bones of the face. There are 6 bones of the cranium (frontal, parietal, occipital, temporal, sphenoid, ethmoid) and 8 bones of the face (zygomatic, maxilla, nasal, lacrimal, vomer, palatine, interior conchae, mandible)

Overall, there are 6 unpaired bones of the skull. These are:
Front
Occipital
Sphenoid
Ethmoid
Mandible
Vomer

q30.text: Which of the following is an unpaired bone of the face?
q30.explanation: The vomer is an unpaired bone of the facial skeleton. It forms the inteferior part of the nasal septum with the superior portion formed by the perpendicular plate of the ethmoid bone and the anterior portion formed by the cartilage of the septum. It is located in the midsagittal line.

q31.text: Which of the following raises the larynx and pharynx during swallowing?
q31.explanation:
The palatopharyngeus raises/shortens the pharynx, raise the larynx, lowers the soft palate and seals the oral cavity.The constrictor muscles play a vital role in the swallowing mechanism. As soon as the bolus arrives in the pharynx, the constrictor muscles contract upon the bolus shunting it downwards into the oesophagus.

The styloglossus draws up one side of the tongue to create a trough to aid swallowing. When the muscles work as a pair they aid in retracting the tongue.

q32.text: True/false: the laryngeal prominence is more apparent in men.
q32.explanation: The laryngeal prominence is also known as the ‘Adam’s Apple’. This is more pronounced in males. This is due to the meeting point of the left and right sides of thyroid cartilage meeting at an angle of around 90°, compared to that of women, which forms an open arc at 120°.

q33.text: The external acoustic meatus is found in which part of the ear?
q33.explanation: The external acoustic meatus is also known as the ear canal. It is the tube running from the visible outer ear (pinna) to the middle ear (ear drug). For the adult human ear, the canal length is typically 2.5cm.

q34.text: Which nerve supplies the sensory innervation for the nasopharynx?
q34.explanation:
For sensory function, the nasopharynx is supplied by maxillary branch of the trigeminal nerve (CN V2), unlike the oropharynx and the laryngopharyx, which are supplied by the pharyngeal plexus via CN IX and CN X.

For motor function, the pharyngeal plexus innervates all the muscles of the pharynx (except the stylopharyngeus) via CN IX, CN X and CN XI. The intrinsic muscles of the larynx are innervated by branches of the vagus nerve exclusively and not the pharyngeal plexus. q35.text: Which of the following is filled with cartilage after birth?
q35.explanation:
The foramen lacerum is a triangular hole that is found at the base of the skull between the sphenoid, basilar part of occipital and apex of petrous temporal. It is situated anteromedial to the carotid canal. After birth, it is filled with cartilage.

The foramen lacerum transmits the small meningeal branches of the ascending pharyngeal artery and emissary veins from the caveronous sinus. The internal carotid artery passes superior to this foramen as it exits the carotid canal, but it does not travel through it.

q36.text: The middle meningeal artery is a branch of the:
q36.explanation:
The middle meningeal artery is the third branch of the first part of the maxillary artery, which arises from the external carotid artery. It enters the middle cranial fossa via the foramen spinosum to supply the dura mater and the calvaria. The middle meningeal artery is the largest of the three paired arteries that supply the meninges. The other two arteries are the posterior and anterior meningeal arteries.

The middle meningeal artery lies beneath the weakest point of the skull, known as the pterion. The pterion is found in the temple region where the frontal, parietal, temporal and sphenoid bones join together. The clinical relevance lies in the fact that injury to the pterion and the underlying middle meningeal artery is the most common cause of an epidural hematoma. Damage is inflicted likely via head injury, such a sports injury or a road traffic collision.

q37.text: True or false: The vestibular fold of the larynx is known as the false vocal cord
q37.explanation: The vestibular fold is a pair of mucous membrane folds that stretches from the angle of the thyroid cartilage to the arytenoid cartilage on each side. The vestibular fold of the larynx plays a crucial role in preventing the pulmonary aspiration of food or drink, by preventing their entry during breathing and speech. It is the contact of food/liquid with the vocal folds that elicits the cough reflex to expel the bolus from the lower pharynx.

q38.text: Which of the following is innervated by the glossopharyngeal nerve?
q38.explanation:
For motor function, the pharyngeal plexus innervates all the muscles of the pharynx (except the stylopharyngeus) via CN IX, CN X and CN XI. The stylopharyngeus is innervated exclusively by the glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX).

The stylopharyngeus originates from the styloid process of the temporal bone to the thyroid cartilage. It aids in swallowing and acts to elevate the larynx and pharynx.

q39.text: The glossopharyngeal nerve is involved with:
q39.correctAnswer: The posterior one-third of the tongue for taste

otherAnswers.a1: The anterior two-thirds of the tongue for motor
otherAnswers.a3: Visceral motor for the submandibular gland

q39.explanation:
Regarding sensory innervation:

Taste and sensation for the posterior one-third of the tongue is innervated by the glossopharyngeal nerve. The anterior two-thirds of the tongue is innervated by the facial nerve (via the chorda tympani) for taste, and the lingual branch of CN V3 for sensation.

For motor function, the entire tongue is innervated by the hypoglossal nerve (CN XII).

The glossopharyngeal nerve has five separate functions. (1) special visceral efferent: motor to the stylopharyngeus. (2) general visceral efferent: motor to the parotid gland via the otic gland. (3) general visceral afferent: sensory from the carotid sinus and carotid body. (4) general somatic afferent: sensory from the posterior one-third of the tongue, upper pharynx and the tympanic membrane (5) special visceral afferent: taste from posterior one-third of the tongue.

q40.text: Which of the following is solely innervated by the hypoglossal nerve?

otherAnswers.a1: All extrinsic muscles of the tongue

q40.explanation:
The hypoglossal nerve supplies motor fibres to all intrinsic and extrinsic muscles of the tongue (except the palatoglossus, which is an extrinsic muscle that is supplied by the vagus nerve via the pharyngeal plexus). The intrinsic tongue muscles are required for controlling fine movements within the tongue for speech, food manipulation and swallowing. This is as opposed to extrinsic muscles of the tongue, which are involved in whole tongue movements.

The stylopharyngeus is supplied by the glossopharyngeal nerve. The buccinator is supplied by the buccal branch of the facial nerve.

q41.correctAnswer: It may show signs of hypertrophy in bruxist patients

otherAnswers.a1: Is it innervated by the maxillary division of the trigeminal nerve
otherAnswers.a2: It has a superficial and lateral head
otherAnswers.a3: It may be palpated clinically by asking the patient to relax their jaws
otherAnswers.a4: It is one of three muscles of mastication.

q41.explanation:
The masseter muscle is a thick muscles with a superficial and deep head that is innervated by the mandibular branch of the trigeminal nerve. It may show signs of hypertrophy (enlargement) in bruxist patients due to their habitual clenching or grinding. Hypertrophy can be assessed by palpating the muscle clinically, by asking the patient to clench their jaws. Due to excessive parafunction, hypertrophy of the masseter may be combined with further pathology of the TMJ.

The master is one of four muscles of mastication. The other muscles in this group are the temporalis, the medial pterygoid and the lateral pterygoid.

q42.correctAnswer: The temporalis inserts into the condyle of the mandible

otherAnswers.a1: All the muscles of mastication except the lateral pterygoid are innervated by the trigeminal nerve
otherAnswers.a2: The lateral pterygoid is involved in depressing the mandible
otherAnswers.a3: They are derived from the second pharyngeal arch
otherAnswers.a4: There are 4 muscles of mastication, but only 3 are paired

q42.explanation: The temporalis inserts into the coronoid process of the mandible. All four muscles of mastication are paired, and they are all innervated by the mandibular branch of the trigeminal nerve, which is a reflection of its development from the first pharyngeal arch. The lateral pterygoid is the only pair of muscles in the group that is involved in depressing the mandible; the other three muscles are involved in elevation of the mandible.

q43.text: Which of the following statements is incorrect regarding the sensation of taste?
q43.correctAnswer: Circumvallate papilla are found scattered across the tip and sides of the tongue

otherAnswers.a1: Fungiform papilla can distinguish between sweet, sour, bitter and salty tastes
otherAnswers.a2: Filiform papilla do not contain taste buds
otherAnswers.a3: The glossopharyngeal nerve carries taste sensation for the posterior one-third of the tongue
otherAnswers.a4: The papillae play a mechanical role during mastication by providing friction

q43.explanation: The circumvallate papilla are found in a V-shape arrangement immediately anterior to the sulcus terminalis, which is the border between the anterior two-thirds and the posterior one-third of the tongue. Fungiform papilla are mushroom-shaped projections on the tongue that are able to distinguish between the four tastes. They are found towards the tip and sides of the tongue. Filiform papillae do not contain taste buds; they act to provide roughness and friction to the tongue surface to aid in mechanical manipulation of the food bolus. The glossopharyngeal nerve carries taste and motor function for the posterior one-third of the tongue.

q44.correctAnswer: Unilateral contraction of the medial pterygoid leads to contralateral excursion of the mandible

otherAnswers.a1: The muscle has a deep and superficial head
otherAnswers.a2: It is innervated directly by the mandibular branch of the trigeminal nerve
otherAnswers.a4: One of its heads originates on the medial surface of the lateral pterygoid plate

q44.explanation:
The lateral pterygoid is divided into superior and inferior heads. It is innervated directly by the lateral pterygoid nerve, which is a branch of the mandibular nerve of the trigeminal nerve. The inferior head originates from the lateral surface of the lateral pterygoid plate. The medial pterygoid originates on the medial aspect of this plate.

Contraction of both lateral pteryfoid muscles as a pair leads to depression of the mandible. However, during unilateral contraction, only one lateral pterygoid in the pair is contracting. Therefore, the mandible is brought over to the side that is relaxed, thus appearing as contralateral excursion.

q45.text: Cranial nerves V, VII and IX are also known as:
q45.explanation:
Cranial nerves are nerves that emerge directly from the brain. They are denoted by roman numerals as shown. A useful rhyme to remember the order of cranial nerves from I to XII is: “Ooh, Ooh, Ooh, to touch and feel very good velvet. Such heaven!”.

CN I – olfactory nerve (smell)

CN II – optic nerve (vision)

CN III – occulomotor (eye movement)

CN IV – trochlear (eye movement)

CN V – trigeminal (face sensation, taste, motor to muscles of mastication)

CN VI - abducens (eye movement)

CN VII – facial nerve (facial expression)

CN VIII – vestibulocochlear (hearing and balance)

CN IX – glossopharyngeal (oral sensation, taste and salivation)

CN X – vagus (heart rate, voice, swallowing)

otherAnswers.a4: The mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve does not exist

q47.explanation: The trigeminal nerve is the fifth cranial nerve (CN V). It is split up into three divisons, notated as V1 (opthalmic), V2 (maxillary) and V3 (mandibular).

q48.text: What is the correct order of branching of the facial nerve?
q48.correctAnswer: Intracranial, meatal, labyrinthine, tympanic, mastoid, extratemporal

otherAnswers.a1: Intracranial, labyrinthine, meatal, tympanic, mastoid, extratemporal

otherAnswers.a3: Intracranial, meatal, tympanic, labyrinthine, mastoid, extratemporal
otherAnswers.a4: Meatal, intracranial, labyrinthine, tympanic, mastoid, extratemporal

q48.explanation:
The correct order for the branching of the facial nerve from its origination in the brain to the superficial strctures of the face is:

Intracranial  - to brainstem

Meatal – brainstem to internal auditory canal

Labyrinthine – internal auditory canal to geniculate ganglion

Tympanic – geniculate ganglion to pyramidal eminence

q1.text: Most dentists work within a _________-handed operative field.
q1.explanation:
A four-handed operative field involves both the dentist and the dental nurse. The operative field is a 360-degree area around the patient. This area is divided into four zones of activity.”  The four zones are: the operator’s zone, assistant’s zone, transfer zone, and static zone.

The position of the patient’s face when lying supine in the dental chair is used as the reference point of 12 o’clock for the purposes of describing the separation of these zones.

For the right-handed dentist, the four zones are located at the following points:
-Operator’s zone 7 to 12 o’clock
-Static zone from 12 to 2 o’clock.
-Assistant’s zone from 2 to 4 o’clock
-Instrument transfer zone from 4 to 7 o’clock

For the left-handed dentists, the four zones are located at the following points:
-Operator’s zone 12 to 5 o’clock
-Instrument transfer zone from 5 to 8 o’clock
-Assistant’s zone from 8 to 10 o’clock
-Static zone from 10 to 12 o’clock

To ensure patient safety, it is important that instruments are only transferred in the ‘transfer zone’. This prevents instruments being transferred over vulnerable areas of the patient such as their face. The static zone is the area of least activity; portable cabinets or equipment may be stored in this zone, as it is unlikely to affect the operative field.

q2.text: The 'cornerstones' of the mouth is a term often used to describe which teeth?
q2.explanation: Maxillary and mandibular canines are also known as the ‘cornerstones’ of the mouth. This is due to canines separating the premolars from the incisors and being placed towards the corners of each dental arch. Canines have a single cusp with their main function being to aid in the tearing of food. Due to the large root size and morphology of the canine tooth, they are able to withstand the significant lateral forces caused by chewing, thus protecting the premolars and molars from such forces during lateral guidance.

q3.correctAnswer: The contact between the maxillary and mandibular teeth

otherAnswers.a1: The distance between the contact points of adjacent teeth
otherAnswers.a2: The relationship between the upper and lower incisors only
otherAnswers.a3: The relationship between the upper and lower molars only
otherAnswers.a4: The blockage of a blood vessel

q3.explanation:
In Dentistry, occlusion refers to the contact between the maxillary and mandibular teeth.

The other incorrect answer options are described below.

The distance between the contact points of adjacent teeth is known as displacement. The horizontal relationship between the upper and lower incisors is known as overjet. The relationship between the upper and lower first permanent molars in a full dental arch may be referred to as molar classification when ascribed to specific tooth surface landmarks. When a vessel is blocked, it is said to be ‘occluded’; however, in Dentistry, this not an acceptable definition for the term ‘occlusion’.

q4.text: When the dentition is divided in six parts, what is the name given to each of these parts?
q4.explanation:
When the upper and lower dentition are divided into a total of six parts, each part is known as a sextant. Sextants are typically used during a BPE exam (basic periodontal exam). Codes are put into each part of the grid to score the teeth found within those sections to inform the clinician of the patient’s periodontal risk and the need for further treatment. In the upper arch, teeth are grouped in the following sextants.

8-4 (right third permanent molar to right first permanent premolar)

3-3 (right canine to left canine)

4-8  (left first premolar to left third permanent molar)

This grouping of tooth is repeated in the lower arch, thus giving six distinct zones, known as sextants.

q5.text: How many canals are most likely to be present in the upper second premolar?
q5.explanation: The upper second premolar contains 1 canal in 90% of cases and 2 canals in 10% of cases.

q6.text: What is the specific name given to the round depression within the surface of a tooth?
q6.explanation:
Fossa is latin for ‘ditch’ or ‘trench’. It describes a depression or hollow in a tissue. Similar in definition, but less frequently used, a fovea is a small cuplike depression or pit in a bone or organ. It would be incorrect to call the depression in the tooth a fovea, as it is not described as such in medical literature, despite its similar definition.

A cusp is an area of elevation on the tooth’s occlusal surface, typically found on the molars and premolars. A fissure is a deep groove in the surface of a structure, such as the deep grooves found on the occlusal surface of permanent molar teeth. A foramen is an opening in the structure of a tissue.

q7.text: What is the result when the secondary tooth pushes on the primary tooth during eruption?
q7.explanation: A reduction in the size of the root of a primary tooth is usually indicative of external resorption, as it occurs on the external surface of the primary tooth. This is due to the physiological response of the primary tooth to the physical impact of the erupting secondary successor against it. The force acting upon the primary tooth increases osteoclast activity, leading to breakdown of the root surface (external resorption). The resorption and loss of the widely splayed primary tooth roots is important to allow the smooth exfoliation of the primary tooth out of the mouth. When you next see an exfoliated primary tooth, note the loss or significant reduction in the size of its roots. This is due to external resorption.

q8.text: What is the name of the process given by the shedding of the primary tooth and replacement by the permanent tooth?
q8.explanation:
Exfoliation is the natural (or physiological) loss and replacement of a tooth by its secondary successor. Eruption is the process in tooth development in which the teeth enter the mouth and become visible. The other terms describe traumatic injuries to a tooth.

Avulsion: the complete displacement of a tooth from its socket in alveolar bone

Subluxation: an injury to the tooth supporting structures resulting in increased mobility, but without displacement of the tooth

Concussion: an injury to the tooth supporting structures without abnormal loosening or displacement of the tooth.

q9.text: What is the name given to the cell associated with the resorption of bone associated with deciduous teeth eruption?
q9.explanation:
An odontoclast is an osteoclast associated with absorption of the roots of deciduous teeth. An odontoblast is a cell in the outer surface of the dental pulp of a tooth that produces dentine.

A fibroblast is a cell in connective tissue which produces collagen, extracellular matrix and other fibres. They are the most common cells of connective tissue in animals. A fibroclast is not a widely recognised cell type, but is thought to be a subtype of fibroblast cells, known for their unusually high activity of degradation.

Fibrinogen is a soluble protein present in blood plasma, from which fibrin is produced by the action of the enzyme thrombin.

q10.text: In history taking, which section is ‘Drinking history’ found in?
q10.explanation: A social history (abbreviated to 'SocHx') addresses familial, occupational, and recreational aspects of a patient's personal life that have the potential to be clinically significant. Other areas to be questioned upon include occupation, travel, exercise and diet

q11.text: In history taking, which section is ‘Sibling history of restorations’ found in?
q11.explanation: The ‘Sibling history of restorations’ would be taken in Dental History, as it concerns itself with the topic of dental treatment.

q12.text: What is the name given to the following mineral - Ca₁₀(PO₄)₆(OH)₂?
q12.explanation:
Hydroxyapatite is a naturally occurring mineral formed from Calcium, Phosphate and Hydoxyl subunits. Hydroxyapatite has the formula Ca₅(PO₄)₃(OH), but it is often written as Ca₁₀(PO₄)₆(OH)₂  to denote the pairing within each crystal unit. The hydroxyl unit is a negatively charged species, and can be replaced by other species with a single negative charge, notably Fluoride, Chloride or Carbonate groups, producing fluorapatite - Ca₁₀(PO₄)₆F₂ - or chlorapatite - Ca₁₀(PO₄)₆Cl₂ - respectively. The crystal mineral is arranged in a hexagonal formation.

Pure hydroxyapatite appears white, but may also appear yellow, brown or green, depending on the replacement of this hydroxyl group. For example, excessive fluoride intake leads to an increased proportion of fluorapatite in the tooth structure. This irregularity in the tooth structure caused by areas of fluorapatite leads to regions of hypomineralisation, leading to white spots, similar in appearance to early enamel white spot lesions. In severe cases, excessive deposition of fluorapatite may lead to undesirable brown staining, pitting or mottling of tooth enamel.

q13.text: The tooth is no longer at risk of dental fluorosis following its eruption into the oral cavity.
q13.explanation:
Chronic excessive fluoride intake during tooth development increases the proportion of fluorapatite in the tooth structure. This irregularity in the tooth structure caused by areas of fluorapatite leads to regions of hypomineralisation, leading to white spots, similar in appearance to early enamel white spot lesions. In severe cases, excessive deposition of fluorapatite may lead to undesirable brown staining, pitting or mottling of tooth enamel.

Following development and eruption of the tooth, the fluorapatite can no longer cause major structural changes in the surface enamel, since it is already formed. The fluorapatite thus provides a beneficial topical effect, as it converts the surface enamel hydroxyapatite to the more acid-resistant fluorapatite.

q14.text: Which is a disease process of hard tissues?
q14.explanation:
Caries is a process of overall demineralisation of the tooth substance leading to destruction of enamel and dentine, which can lead to the cavitation of the tooth. Caries is classified as a disease as it is a pathological infection caused by bacterial invasion of the tooth.

Erosion and abrasion are categories of tooth wear. Erosion is defined as the irreversible loss of tooth structure due to chemical dissolution by acids not of bacterial origin. Abrasion is the loss of tooth structure by mechanical forces from a foreign element.

Avulsion and subluxation are categories of dental trauma. Avulsion is the complete displacement of a tooth from its socket in alveolar bone. Subluxation is an injury to the tooth supporting structures resulting in increased mobility, but without displacement of the tooth.

q15.text: Which of the following structures has a 96% inorganic component
q15.explanation: Enamel is the hardest substance in the human body and consisting of a 96% mineral content. The primary mineral is hydroxyapatite, which is a crystalline calcium phosphate. Water and organic material composes the other 4% of enamel. Dentine and cementum are composed of 70% and 45-50% inorganic component respectively.

q16.text: Which of the following is the name given to the tooth surface closest to the cheek?
q16.explanation:
The surfaces of the tooth are labelled with the following terms:

Mesial – the surface of the tooth closest to the midline of the dental arch

Distal – the surface of the tooth first from the midline of the dental arch

Buccal – the surface of the tooth closest to the cheek (think 'buccinator')

Lingual/palatal – the surface of the tooth closest to the tongue/palate

Occlusal – the biting surface of premolar and molar teeth, or the surface of a tooth that comes in contact with the opposing arch during function

Incisal – the cutting edge of incisors and canines

q17.text: Which of the following is the name given to the tooth surface closest to the tongue?
q17.explanation:
The surfaces of the tooth are labelled with the following terms:

Mesial – the surface of the tooth closest to the midline of the dental arch

Distal – the surface of the tooth first from the midline of the dental arch

Buccal – the surface of the tooth closest to the cheek (think 'buccinator')

Lingual/palatal – the surface of the tooth closest to the tongue/palate

Occlusal – the biting surface of premolar and molar teeth, or the surface of a tooth that comes in contact with the opposing arch during function

q18.text: Which of the following is the name given to the surface of the tooth furthest away from the midline?
q18.explanation:
The surfaces of the tooth are labelled with the following terms:

Mesial – the surface of the tooth closest to the midline of the dental arch

Distal – the surface of the tooth first from the midline of the dental arch

Buccal – the surface of the tooth closest to the cheek (think 'buccinator')

Lingual/palatal – the surface of the tooth closest to the tongue/palate

Occlusal – the biting surface of premolar and molar teeth, or the surface of a tooth that comes in contact with the opposing arch during function

Incisal – the cutting edge of incisors and canines

q19.text: Which of the following is the name given to the biting surface of the tooth?
q19.explanation:
The surfaces of the tooth are labelled with the following terms:

Mesial – the surface of the tooth closest to the midline of the dental arch

Distal – the surface of the tooth first from the midline of the dental arch

Buccal – the surface of the tooth closest to the cheek (think 'buccinator')

Lingual/palatal – the surface of the tooth closest to the tongue/palate

Occlusal – the biting surface of premolar and molar teeth, or the surface of a tooth that comes in contact with the opposing arch during function

Incisal – the cutting edge of incisors and canines

q20.text: A dentist notates an upper left canine as 23. What dental notation format was used?
q20.explanation:
This tooth is an upper left canine. FDI is a 2-digit dental notation. The first digit (1-4) indicates the tooth quadrant, running clockwise from upper right to lower right; the second digit indicates the tooth position from first incisor to third molar (1-8).

FDI notation is widely used by dentists to chart teeth. It was developed by the FDI world dental federation. This notation is also known as ISO 3950 notation. Like palmer’s notation, the chart orientation is in the ‘dentist’s view’ – the patient’s right corresponds to notation on the left half the chart.

The Palmers notation is a dental notation system to chart specific teeth. It is also know the the ‘Military System’. It is the most predominant dental notation system used in the UK.  The teeth are grouped in each of the four quadrants (upper left, upper right, lower left, lower right) and numbered 1-8. Like FDI notation, the chart orientation is in the ‘dentist’s view’ – the notation on the right half the char corresponds to the patient’s left.

q21.text: A dentist notates an upper right third molar as 1 on a dental chart. Which dental notation method was used?
q21.explanation:
The Universal Numbering System is a dental notation system to chart specific teeth. It is commonly used in the United States but it is not as common elsewhere. The designations 'left' and 'right' on the chart correspond to the patient's left and right, respectively.

The chart runs from 1-32 for permanent teeth, counting the teeth in anti-clockwise order from the upper right permanent third molar to the lower right permanent third molar. Primary teeth are counted from A-T in anti-clockwise order from the upper right primary second molar to the lower right primary second molar.

q22.text: How many roots does the maxillary first permanent molar have most commonly?
q22.explanation: The maxillary first permanent molar has three roots: 1 palatal, 1 mesiobuccal and 1 distobuccal. The mandibular first permanent molar has two roots: 1 mesial and 1 distal.

q23.text: How many roots does the mandibular first permanent molar have most commonly?
q23.explanation: The mandibular first permanent molar has two roots: 1 mesial and 1 distal; and most commonly two root canals. The maxillary first permanent molar has three roots: 1 palatal, 1 mesiobuccal and 1 distobuccal; and most commonly three root canals.

q24.text: How many root canals does the mandibular first permanent incisor have most commonly?
q24.explanation: The mandibular first permanent incisor has one root and one root canal.

q25.text: How many roots does the maxillary first permanent premolar have most commonly?
q25.explanation: The maxillary first permanent premolar has two roots. However, the maxillary second premolar has just one root.

q26.text: How many root canals does the maxillary second permanent premolar have most commonly?
q26.explanation:
In 40% of cases, this tooth has one root canal. In 58% of cases the tooth may have two canals.

Bellizi R, Hartwell G. Radiographic evaluation of root canal anatomy of in vivoendodontically treated maxillary premolars. J Endod 1985; 11: 37–39.

q27.text: How many root canals does the mandibular first permanent premolar have most commonly?
q27.explanation:
This tooth typically has one root with one root canal. However, in 25% of cases this canal may divide into two canals and two apical foramina, as described by Vertucci.

Zillich R, Dowson J. Root canal morphology of the mandibular first and second premolars. Oral Surg 1973; 36: 738–744.

q28.text: How many root canals does the mandibular second permanent premolar have most commonly?
q28.explanation:
This tooth typically has one root with one root canal. The incidence of a second canal with a second apical foramen is much lower than that of the mandibular first permanent premolar, with reported incidence rates of 2.5-12% between different studies. Thus, it can be a much easier tooth to treat compared to the first permanent premolar.

P Carrotte. (2004). Endodontics: Part 4 Morphology of the root canal system. British Dental Journal 197(1), pp. 379 - 383

q29.text: An upper first permanent molar has:

otherAnswers.a4: 1 buccal root, 1 palatal root and 1 mesial root

q29.explanation: The upper first permanent molar has three roots in total: 1 palatal root, 1 mesiobuccal root and 1 mesiodistal root.

q30.text: This is the formula of calcium hydroxyapatite [Ca₁₀PO₄F₂]
q30.explanation:
The formula given is that of Fluorapatite, due to the substitution of the terminal OH- [hydroxyl] group for the F- [fluoride] group.

Substitution can occur during physiological development, from ingestion of fluoride. Excessive consumption of fluoride during development can lead to dental fluorosis, caused by areas in the teeth with high levels of Fluorapatite, imparting a discolouration to the tooth ranging from a subtle white spot to brown staining, pitting or mottling of the enamel.

Substitution for the fluoride group may also occur following eruption, from topical contact with fluoride via fluoride supplements. This includes toothpaste, mouthrinses, fluoride tablets and fluoridated water. In erupted teeth, it should be noted that no further physiological development of the visible crown occurs [the root, however, may still be forming]. Therefore, dental fluorosis cannot develop in the crowns of already erupted teeth.

Fluorapatite’s main advantage over its precursor, calcium hydroxyapatite, is its greater resistance to dissolution by acid attack. This is due to its inherently lesser solubility in acid and stronger internal bonding arrangement.

q31.text: Which of the following options is most useful in preventing caries?
q31.explanation:
Fluoride may be found in toothpaste, mouthrinses or drinking water. The US Center for Disease Control has reputed fluoridated drinking water as one of the “ten greatest public health achievements of the 20th century”.

When fluoride is found in saliva, they exert a topical effect by converting the standard calcium hydroxyapatite in the enamel surface to fluorapatite. Fluorapatite’s main advantage over its precursor, calcium hydroxyapatite, is its greater resistance to dissolution by acid attack. This is due to its inherently lesser solubility in acid and stronger internal bonding arrangement.

Fluoride also has the ability to inhibit bacterial acid production by affecting bacterial glycolysis. In this way, remineralisation is promoted and, over time, non-cavitated carious lesions may have an increased chance to arrest.

q32.text: In prosthetics, 'the natural or implanted tooth support/anchorage for the prosthetic tooth' is known as:
q32.explanation:
The definition of the following terms are given:

Abutment: the natural or implanted tooth support/anchorage for the prosthetic tooth

Pontic: the artificial tooth on a bridge or partial denture that replaces the space of the natural crown

Connector: the part of a partial denture that joins the components

Bridge: a fixed partial denture, that restores one or more missing teeth as a functional unit. It consists of an abutment and pontic splinted together.

Crown: the visible part of the tooth; also may refer to the dental prosthesis that replaces the area of tooth covered with enamel.

q33.text: In the permanent dentition, the cusp of Carabelli is typically associated with the:
q33.explanation: The cusp of Carabelli (or Carabelli’s tubercle) is a small additional cusp found on the mesiopalatal aspect of some maxillary first molars. It may also be found in second and third molars, but this is less likely. It has no major clinical significance other than being aware of it during the placement of a fissure sealant.

q34.text: Which of the following teeth has the longest root
q34.explanation: The permanent maxillary canine typically has the longest root in the human dentition with an average length of 27mm. In some schools of thought, it is often prudent to retain maxillary canines that have a good prognosis for complete dentures patients. In this way, the canines may be used an over-abutment whilst aiding retention, maintaining bone levels in that region and preserving proprioceptive function.

q35.text: Pronounced protuberances of the occlusal surface are known as:
q35.explanation:
The pronounced rounded protuberances on the occlusal surface of teeth are known as cusps. They are particularly found on premolar and molar teeth. The cusps provides a three-dimensional arrangement of the tooth surface to allow for powerful grinding action between the cusps of opposing arches. Some individuals (prevalence = 57.6%) have an additional cusp on the upper first permanent molar, known as the Cusp of Carabelli. This is a non-functional cusp.

A fossa is the depression on the occlusal surface of the tooth, within which the food bolus is contained to be ground between the opposing dental arch. A fissure is the deep linear cleft between the cusp and ridges of the tooth. A pit is a sharp-pointed depression in the enamel surface of a tooth caused by faulty calcification or formed by the union of two or more lobes of enamel to form a point structure.

A foramen is a hole in a structure, usually through which vasculature and nerves pass through. This term is often applied to bones of the facial skeleton.

Shethri, Salah Al. 'The Prevalence Of The Carabelli Cusp In Selected Saudi Population'. King Saud University Journal of Dental Sciences 2.1-2 (2011): 13-16. Web.

q36.text: Roots of teeth have mesial inclination
q36.explanation: Roots of teeth have a distal inclination

q37.text: What is the name of the area of tooth covered by cementum?
q37.explanation:
The root of a tooth is the part of the tooth embedded into the alveolar socket. It is surrounded by a substance called cementum, which is thickets at the root apex. Cementum anchors the tooth into the socket via fibres of the periodontal ligament.  Cementum is produced by cementoblasts which eventually become entrapped in the deposited cementum to become cementocytes. Unlike enamel. cementum is capable of limited self-repair.

The crown is the part of the tooth that is visible in the mouth above the gums. The pulp is the vascular component of a tooth supplying blood and containing the nerves to innervate the tooth via the apical foramen of the tooth. The gingiva is name given to the firm tissue surrounding the necks of teeth, also known as the gums. The periodontal ligament is a specialised connective tissue that attaches a tooth to the associated alveolar bone socket (a ligament attaches bone to bone).

q38.text: What is the name given to the area of natural tooth contained within the alveolar bone?
q38.explanation: The clinical crown is just the part of the tooth that is visible in the mouth, whereas the anatomical crown is full entire enamel-covered part of a tooth, including the area hidden within the gums. There is no such term as the biological root. The clinical root is simply the part of the tooth that is embedded into the alveolar socket. An implant abutment is an artificial tooth root that is osseointegrated into the alveolar socket to provide stability and retention to the overlying prosthesis.

q39.text: How many cusps are present on the LR4?
q39.explanation:
There are just two cusps on the LR4 (also called the mandibular first permanent premolar). One large cusp is found on the buccal side; the other cusp on the lingual side is small and non-functional. The first premolar is often synonymously term ‘bicuspid’. However, the term ‘bicuspid’ only technically refers to a tooth that has two functional cusps.

Due to the large prominent of the buccal cusp, the LR4 closely resembles a canine tooth.

q40.text: How many cusps are present on the mandibular left permanent second premolar (LL5)?
q40.explanation: The mandibular left permanent second premolar (LL5) has three cusps. One large cusp is found on the buccal side; the other two cusps are found on the lingual side. The mesiolingual cusp is twice the size of the distolingual cusp.

q41.text: Regarding the mandibular second premolar, the mesiolingual cusp is twice the size of the distolingual cusp.
q41.explanation: The mandibular permanent second premolar has three cusps. One large cusp is found on the buccal side; the other two cusps are found on the lingual side. The mesiolingual cusp is twice the size of the distolingual cusp.

q42.text: How many cusps are present on the mandibular right permanent first molar (LR6)?
q42.explanation: The mandibular right permanent first molar (LR6) has five cusps. In order of decreasing size, the cusps are MB, ML, DL, DB and D.

q43.text: How many cusps are most commonly present on the maxillary left permanent first molar (UL6)?
q43.explanation: The maxillary left permanent first molar (UL6) has four cusps – MB, DB, ML and DL.  In some cases, there may be a fifth smaller cusp, on the palatal side termed the Cusp of Carabelli.

q44.text: How many cusps are present on the mandibular permanent second molar (LR7)?
q44.explanation: The mandibular permanent second molar (LR7) has four cusps – MB, DB, ML and DL.

q45.text: The linear cleft between the cusps and ridges of a tooth is known as a __________.
q45.explanation:
A fissure is a deep groove in the surface of a structure, such as the deep grooves found on the occlusal surface of permanent molar teeth. A pit is a sharp-pointed depression or hollow in the tooth enamel surface, usually formed at the union of two or more lobes of enamel.

A cusp is an area of elevation on the tooth’s occlusal surface, typically found on the molars and premolars. A foramen is an opening in the structure of a tissue. Fossa is latin for ‘ditch’ or ‘trench’. It describes a depression or hollow in a tissue. Similar in definition, but less frequently used, a fovea is a small cuplike depression or pit in a bone or organ. It would be incorrect to call the depression in the tooth a fovea, as it is not described as such in medical literature, despite its similar definition.

q46.text: Junction between the root and anatomical crown
q46.explanation:
The interface between the tooth root and anatomical crown is termed the cervical margin. It also known as the neck of the tooth.

The CEJ also lies in this region, which represents the beginning of the layer of cementum from the enamel. The cementum covers the root dentine surface, to aid in anchorage of the root into the alveolar socket via the periodontal ligament. In 30% of the teeth the cementum and enamel in this region are abut with each other. However, in 60% of cases, the cementum slightly overlaps the enamel at the CEJ (Carranza & Bernard, 2002)

The ADJ represents the internal boundary between the enamel and underlying dentine. It is a boundary only visible in a cross-section view of the tooth.

The gingival margin is the most coronal part of the free gingiva. Biological width is the distance between the most coronal point of the junctional epithelium to the most coronal point of the alveolar crest. The average biological width in an adult individual is 2.04mm (Mishkin & Gellin, 1993).

The mucogingival junction is the interface between the non-keratinised oral mucosa and the highly keratinised attached gingiva. In some patients a clear delineation between these two portions of mucosa is visible, due to their difference in keratinisation.

Ref: Carranza FA, Bernard GW (2002). 'The Tooth-Supporting Structures'. In Newman MG, Takei HH, Carranza FA. Carranza’s Clinical Periodontology (9th ed.). Philadelphia: W. B. Saunders. p. 43

Mishkin DJ, Gellin RG. Re: Biologic width and crown lengthening. J Periodontol 1993; 64:920

q47.text: Nicotine does not cross blood-brain barrier
q47.explanation: Following inhalation, nicotine-rich blood is quickly circulated through the body. Nicotine can cross the blood-brain barrier. 10-20 seconds after inhalation, the nicotine can reach the brain and exert its psychogenic effects. The elimination half-life of nicotine is approximately two hours.

q48.text: The cutting edge of anterior teeth is known as the ____________.
q48.explanation:
The incisal edge is the cutting edge of anterior teeth. Cusps are the raised protuberances found on the occlusal surface of premolars and  molars. The term ‘advancing edge’ is used in conjunction with histological caries diagnosis. The advancing edge is the deepest portion of a carious lesion – the part that is advancing further into the tooth. An anterior open bite is an orthodontic diagnosis of malocclusion, whereby there is an open space between the upper and lower anterior teeth.  Knife edge is a term to describe the shape of an edentulous ridge. A ridge that is knife-edged has sufficient height but insufficient width, so appears thin and ‘knife-like in shape. A knife-edged ridge is classed as an Atwood Class IV ridge.

The other Atwood classifications to describe the state of the alveolar ridge are given below:

Atwood Class I – a tooth bearing ridge

Atwood Class II – a ridge immediately post-extraction

Atwood Class III – a high and well rounded ridge

Atwood Class IV – a knife-edged ridge

Atwood Class V – a depressed ridge

q49.text: True or false: GIC adheres to dentine.
q49.explanation: GIC can adhere to dentine, even in cases of poor moisture control. This makes GIC particularly useful as a restorative option for cervical lesions that are close to the gingiva and the nearly transudate/exudate.  GIC forms an ionic bond with dentine via two carboxyl (COO-) groups in the cement and the calcium (Ca2+) in the dentine.

q50.text: How many teeth exist in the permanent dentition?
q50.explanation: In normal physiology, the adult human has 32 teeth in the secondary dentition - 8 teeth within each of the 4 quadrants.

q51.text: How many teeth exist in the deciduous dentition?
q51.explanation: In normal physiology, there are 20 teeth in the deciduous (primary) dentition - 5 teeth within each of the 4 quadrants. In each quadrant, there are 2 incisors, 1 canine and 2 molar teeth. There are no premolars in the primary dentition.

q52.text: What is the name given to the dentine that is formed throughout life?

otherAnswers.a4: Dentine is not formed within the tooth following its eruption

q52.explanation: There are three types of dentine – primary, secondary and tertiary. Secondary is the dentine that is formed throughout life. Primary dentine is formed during tooth development, and forms the bulk of the dentine in the tooth and forms the structural architecture of the tooth. Production of secondary begins after root completion but continues throughout life. Tertiary dentine is produced in response to a noxious stimulus, such as caries or trauma. Tertiary dentine can be classified as reactionary or reparative. Reactionary dentine is formed by pre-existing odontoblasts, whereas repatative is produced by newly differentiated odontoblast-like cells, deriving from pulpal progenitor cells.

q53.text: The congenital absence of six or more teeth is known as:
q53.explanation:
Oligodontia is the congenital absence of six or more teeth, excluding 3rd molars. Anodontia is the congenital absence of all primary or permanent teeth. It is associated with a group of skin and nerve syndromes termed the Ectodermal Dysplasias (EDs).

Hypodontia is the congenital absence of up to five permanent teeth. The order of prevalence of teeth that are congenitally absent are 3rd molars, followed by the lower 5s, the upper 2s and the upper 5s. Hyperdontia is the condition of having one or more additional teeth (supernumerary) to the dentition.

Maldontia is not a recognised terminology.

q54.text: The tip of the root of a tooth is known as the:
q54.explanation:
The apex of a tooth is very tip of the tooth root. It contains the apical foramen, which is the point of entry/exit for nerves and blood vessels supplying the dental pulp.

The crown is the part of a tooth that is covered by enamel. The clinical crown is the part of the enamel-covered tooth that is seen in the oral cavity. The anatomical crown is the entire area above the cement-enamel junction (CEJ) that is covered in enamel, including the enamel hidden by the surrounding gingiva.

The cusp is the raised protuberances on the occlusal surface of premolars and molars. Enamel is the hard, mineralised top-surface of teeth that appears white.

The root eminence is not a recognised terminology.

q55.text: What term is used for the congenital absence of all teeth?
q55.explanation:
Anodontia is a rare genetic disorder characterised by the congenital absence of all primary or permanent teeth. Oligodontia is the congenital absence of six or more teeth, excluding 3rd molars.

Hypodontia is the congenital absence of up to five permanent teeth. The order of prevalence of teeth that are congenitally absent are 3rd molars, followed by the lower 5s, the upper 2s and the upper 5s. Hyperdontia is the condition of having one or more additional teeth (supernumerary) to the dentition.

Maldontia is not a recognised terminology.

q56.text: Fill in the blank space with an appropriate answer option. Lidocaine hydrochloride is commonly used as a(n) _________________ in dental practice.
q56.explanation:
Lidocaine hydrochloride (also known as xylocaine and lignocaine) is a common anaesthetic used in dental practice. An aesthetic is a medication used to numb tissues in a specific area. It acts to stop depolarisation of the affected nerve by blocking sodium channels, thus preventing signal induction.  After injection, the effects begin within 4-7 minutes and can last up to 2-3 hours.

Lidocaine is an amino-amide anaesthetic. It is safe for use in pregnancy. Lidocaine is often combined with a small amount of adrenaline (epinephrine) to constrict the local blood supply to localise the lidocaine to a smaller area, so doses have a longer duration of effect.

q57.text: The first set of teeth that a healthy infant develops is technically termed the:
q57.explanation:
The primary (or deciduous) dentition is the first set of teeth that erupts into the oral cavity. There are 20 teeth in the primary dentition. The first tooth erupts at 6 months of age. These teeth are known in layman’s terms as ‘milk teeth’.

The secondary (or permanent) dentition is the second set of teeth that erupt into the oral cavity to replace the primary dentition. There are 32 teeth in the secondary dentition. The first secondary teeth to erupt are the first permanent molars, at 6 years of age. These teeth are known in layman’s terms as ‘adult teeth’.

q58.correctAnswer: Releases fluoride into the oral cavity over time

otherAnswers.a1: Fluoride release is maintained by fluoride varnish
otherAnswers.a2: Relies on the formation of a hybrid layer
otherAnswers.a4: Relies on covalent bonding between the cement and the tooth surface

q58.explanation:
GIC is a widely used dental restorative material. It is composed of a silicate glass powder, a polyalkenoic acid and an ionomer. An ionomer is a polymer that contains an ion. They contain non-ionic repeating units and a small amount (less than 15% of total polymer) of ion-containing repeating units. They rely on ionic bonds between the carboxyl (COO-) group of the polyalkeloid and the Ca2+ group within the hydroxyapatite crystals of tooth tissue. GIC bonds best to moist dentine.

The hybrid layer is formed during the application of an adhesive bond (unfilled resin) before the placement of a composite resin. It does not apply to GIC.

q59.text: Look at the image of the bur. Which of the following is correct regarding this bur?
q59.correctAnswer: Should be used with a water coolant

otherAnswers.a1: Is used in a slow handpiece
otherAnswers.a3: It can reach speeds up to a maximum of 200,000 RPM
otherAnswers.a4: It is called a rose-head bur

q59.explanation: The bur shown in the picture is known as a flame composite finishing bur. It is used in a fast-handpiece, via a friction-grip mechanism. A fast handpiece can reach speeds over 200,000 RPM (up to 450,000 RPM in some handpieces). Because of the high speed of this bur and the resultant friction caused with the tooth tissue, it is imperative to use a water coolant. This acts to prevent heat necrosis of the pulp as well as avoiding burning the tooth or restorative material.

q60.text: You are charting the teeth of an 11-year-old female patient. Which teeth are likely to be seen as partially erupting in the oral cavity?
q60.explanation: An 11-year-old patient would present with their upper 126 and lower 1236. The upper 3 and lower 45 are likely to be partially erupted into the oral cavity.  The upper 3 erupts at 11-12 years; the upper and lower premolars (45) erupt between 10-12 years of age. The lower 3 erupts at 9-10 years so is likely to be fully erupted by age 11.

q61.text: What is the estimated daily production of saliva in a healthy person?
q61.explanation: An estimated 0.75 – 1.50 L of saliva is produced per day by a healthy individual. However, during sleep, the amount of saliva produced falls to almost 0. The submandibular gland contributes 70-75% of all salivary secretions, while the parotid gland (although the largest salivary gland) contributes 20-25%.

q62.text: What is normal horizontal tooth movement in the socket?
q62.explanation:
The periodontal ligament has a natural flexibility to cushion forces on the teeth during function (chewing), thus reducing the risk of tooth fracture. Physiological (normal) tooth mobility is 0.2 mm. Any movement greater than this would indicate abnormal tooth mobility.

Mobility is clinically assessed by applying pressure from the handle ends of two dental mirrors between the buccal and lingual aspects of each tooth. The assessed mobility is then categorised into one of three types, according to Preston D. Miller:

N/A – < 0.2 mm mobility in horizontal plane

Type I – 0.2 - 1 mm mobility in horizontal plane

Type II – > 1 mm mobility in horizontal plane

Type II – > 1 mm mobility in the horizontal and vertical plane

q63.text: How many grams of pressure should be applied to the BPE probe during a BPE examination?
q63.explanation:
During a BPE examination, it important to exert the correct amount of force (20-25g) into the periodontal pocket to prevent over- or under- estimates of the probing depth. As a practical guide, the weight applied should only be enough to blanche the nails. Other factors that may alter the probing depth are:

-Existing calculus (subgingival obstruction)
-Varied root anatomy
-Angle of the probe
-Probe thickness
-Operator subjectivity (rounding measurements up/down)
-Gingival inflammation (false pocketing)
-Accuracy of the reference point
-Operator experience

Ref: Al Shayeb, K., Turner, W. and Gillam, D. (2014). In-vitro accuracy and reproducibility evaluation of probing depth measurements of selected periodontal probes. The Saudi Dental Journal, 26(1), pp.19-24.

q64.text: When tooth enamel is exposed to fluoride, a displacement reaction occurs. What group is replaced for fluoride?
q64.explanation:
The hydroxyl unit is a negatively charged species, and can be replaced by other species with a single negative charge, notably Fluoride or Chloride groups, producing fluorapatite - Ca10(PO4)6F2 - or chlorapatite - Ca₁₀(PO₄)₆Cl₂ - respectively. The crystal mineral is arranged in a hexagonal formation. Hydroxyapatite is a naturally occurring mineral formed from Calcium, Phosphate and Hydoxyl subunits. Hydroxyapatite has the formula Ca₅(PO₄)₃(OH), but it is often written as Ca₁₀(PO₄)₆(OH)₂  to denote the pairing within each crystal unit.

Pure hydroxyapatite appears white, but may also appear yellow, brown or green, depending on the replacement of this hydroxyl group. For example, excessive fluoride intake leads to an increased proportion of fluorapatite in the tooth structure. This irregularity in the tooth structure caused by areas of fluorapatite leads to regions of hypomineralisation, leading to white spots, similar in appearance to early enamel white spot lesions. In severe cases, excessive deposition of fluorapatite may lead to undesirable brown staining, pitting or mottling of tooth enamel.

Strontium (Sr²⁺) has a similar structure to calcium, and so it can replace lost calcium ions in the tooth tissue. In this way, it can block exposed tubules in the dentinal tissue, thus reducing symptoms of dentine hypersensitivity caused by hydrodynamic fluid movement. ‘Sensitive’ toothpastes may contain strontium as an active ingredient in the form of strontium acetate and strontium chloride.
