q2.text: What is the use of the equipment shown in the image below?
q2.correctAnswer: To dry the root canal following cleaning and shaping

otherAnswers.a1: As a permanent root canal filling material following cleaning and shaping
otherAnswers.a2: To shape the root canal during endodontic treatment
otherAnswers.a3: To assess the depth of a periodontal pocket
otherAnswers.a4: To extirpate necrotic pulp during root canal therapy

q2.explanation:
The attached image shows paper points, also known as absorbent points. Paper points are tightly rolled up pieces of paper that are inserted into the root canals to dry their contents following cleaning and shaping during endodontic therapy. Following drying, the root canal system is prepared for placement of an obturating material, such as gutta percha.

The clinician should choose the paper point that matches the largest file taken to the working length. Functionally, paper points are rigid enough to be easily inserted and withdrawn whilst retaining sufficient integrity when wet. Paper points may also be soaked in a disinfectant solution and introduced into a canal over to have a prolonged effect.

Paper point technique

Paper points can be used to estimate the working length of a root canal. This concept is derived from the fact that when the contents of a root canal are removed, the root canal is kept dry. Despite the contents of the canal being removed, the extra-radicular environment remains living and hydrated, with blood pus and granulation tissue. If a paper point remains within the apical foramen in a dried canal, it would be returned dry. If a paper point is extended beyond the apical foramen in a dried canal, the part that extended beyond the cavosurface of the canal would return with fluid. Due to the capillary action of fluid, the part of the point that is seen to be wet is an overestimate of the extension beyond the apical foramen, but the point should not be placed into the canal long enough for this action to occur significantly. The length of the canal (to the cavosurface of the apical foramen) is defined as the maximum length that a paper point can be inserted into a canal whilst remaining dry. The master apical file is then chosen. This is defined as the first file that binds (i.e. apical stop) at or just before the paper point length when inserted passively into the canal.

Ref: Dr. Rosenberg. (2003). The Paper Point Technique: Part 1. http://www.dentistrytoday.com/endodontics/1106--sp-1365656792 [Online]. Accessed 24th November 2015.

q3.text: All the following are recognised uses of a matrix band except for one. Which is the exception?
q3.correctAnswer: To increase the chance of overhangs following restoration of a Class III cavity

otherAnswers.a2: To help protect the adjacent tooth from iatrogenic damage
otherAnswers.a3: To recreate the natural tooth shape and interproximal contact
otherAnswers.a4: To restore anatomic proximal contours and contact areas

q3.explanation:
A matrix band is a strip of metal that is placed and tightened around a tooth via a holding mechanism. This band acts to surround the external walls of the tooth, to allow the filling material to be contained within the tooth margins whilst preventing the material from contacting (and bonding to) the adjacent tooth. By acting as an interproximal wall it allows you to achieve the correct tooth contour without overhangs.

The placement of a wedge underneath the contact point, interproximally, is important in the placement of a matrix band to press the matrix band against the narrower neck of the tooth. Without a wedge, the filling material can leak under the contact point, leading to gingival ledges or overhangs.

Overhangs are areas of restoration that do not fit the contour of the tooth. They are iatrogenically caused (i.e. caused by the dental clinician). Overhangs result in sharp or bulky areas of restoration that are often difficult to access and clean, and thus act as plaque retention factors. In this way, overhangs may create or exacerbate pre-existing periodontal conditions as well as increasing the risk of secondary caries to the associated or adjacent tooth.

q4.text: What is the name of the name of the bur shown in the image below?
q4.explanation:
This image shows a chamfer bur (also known as a round- end taper bur), which is recognised by its 6 degree axial taper and rounded end. A chamfer bur is most commonly used in crown preparations to create a 'chamfer finishing line' which represents a clear junction between the tooth preparation area and the unprepared clinical crown.

The other answer options are described below:

Shoulder bur: Also known as flat-end taper bur. Has a 6 degree axial taper with a flat end for crown preparation

Modified shoulder bur: This bur is a combination of both the shoulder and chamfer burs. It allows for a rounded internal angle and a flat 90 degree exit angle

Pear bur: a bur with a slightly inverted cone shaped that is directed towards the shank. The cone shape provides rounded internal line angles and point angles ideal for composite restorations

Rosehead bur: this is a round bur that is often used to gain entry into a cavity , removal of caries and preparation of retention grooves.

q5.text: What is the main function of the piece of equipment shown in the image below?
q5.correctAnswer: For imparting shine onto the restoration surface by a rubbing motion

otherAnswers.a3: For removing and recontouring areas of unsupported enamel
otherAnswers.a4: For carving anatomical features and trim excess materials

q5.explanation:
A burnisher is a precision dental instrument used to impart shine onto a restoration surface by its rubbing action. It has a smooth and bulbous working end that is ideally used to polish the surface of amalgam restorations to give a surface lustre. However it can also be used to shape composite or glass ionomer cements before they set.

The other pieces of equipment in this question are described below:

Excavator: For removal of carious dentine

Flat plastic: For composite placement and contouring

Chisel: For removing and recontouring areas of unsupported enamel

Carver: For carving anatomical features and trim excess materials

q6.text: True or false: the bur shown in the image below should be used with a fast handpiece.
q6.explanation:
The image shows a latch-grip rosehead bur made from tungsten-carbide metal. The visible notch to the left of the bur indicates that it is to be used with a slow-speed handpiece, as these handpieces are designed to latch around the notch to mechanically keep the bur in place during function.

A bur without a notch is known as a friction-grip bur. These burs are used with a fast-speed handpiece. As the name would suggest, these burs are kept in place by a friction-grip.

q7.text: All the following statements are recognised uses of a rubber dam (dental dam) except one. Which is the exception?
q7.correctAnswer: To improve the operator's orientation of the tooth

otherAnswers.a1: For moisture isolation of a tooth
otherAnswers.a2: To prevent aspiration during the placement of an indirect restoration
otherAnswers.a3: To prevent contamination of the root canal system
otherAnswers.a4: To assess for tooth sensitivity to heat using boiling water

q7.explanation:
A rubber dam does not improve the operator's orientation of the tooth. By masking all other anatomical landmarks surrounding the tooth, the operator has a reduced positioning orientation. This is especially true when viewing the tooth under indirect vision (using the dental mirror to view the tooth).

All other statements regarding the use of a rubber dam are correct.

q8.text: Read the following statements about dental burs. All the statements are true except for one. Identify the exception.
q8.correctAnswer: The shank of a bur is the working end

otherAnswers.a1: Latch-grip burs are used with slow handpieces
otherAnswers.a2: Straight-bladed burs cut smoother than crosscut burs
otherAnswers.a3: Operative burs are used for cavity preparation
otherAnswers.a4: Trimming and finishing burs have more blades than operative burs

q8.explanation:
The shank of any instrument is the part that holds the working end (the part that carries out the function of the instrument). All the other statements are true.

Latch-grip burs are used with slow handpieces, as they rely on a mechanical grip to keep the bur in place. Friction-grip burs are used with fast handpieces, which rely on a friction-grip to keep the bur in place.

Straight-bladed burs cut smoother than crosscut burs due to their uniformity in blade position. However, they cut slower than crosscut burs, which has additional cuts across the blade to improve their cutting efficiency. Crosscut burs are found to have a reduced risk of debris being picked up on the bur, improving its speed of cut.

Trimming and finishing burs have more blades than operative burs. To provide a more polishing function, the blades are closer together and shallower.

As the name would suggest, operative burs are used in the main operative components of dentistry (tooth and cavity preparation). They are also known as cavity preparation burs. These burs have deep and wide flutes to allow to aggressively and efficiently cut through enamel.

q9.text: What is the RPM of a highspeed handpiece?
q9.explanation: A high-speed (HS) handpiece operates between 250,000  to 420,000 RPM.  HS handpeices are air-driven. This results in a low torque but high resistance on material contact. This resistance leads to a significant speed (RPM) drop of the bur by up to 40% or more depending on hardness of material. As resistance builds up, the air pressure is unable to maintain the speed of the bur rotation. Electric handpieces are reputed to offer a smoother, more consistent speed during function as the bur is not reliant on air but electricity.

q10.text: What is the RPM of a slowspeed handpiece?
q10.explanation:
A slow-speed (SS) handpiece typically functions at an upper range of 20,000 RPM, although different manufacturers produce handpieces to different speeds (up to 50,000 RPM). A high-speed (HS) handpiece typically operates up to 400,000 RPM.

The reason for the significant difference in speed is due to each handpiece's function. A HS handpiece is used to cut mineralised enamel, which is roughly 4.2 times harder than dentine. The reduced speed of the SS handpiece can be used to remove the softer carious or necrotic dentine whilst ensuring that the harder uninfected dentine and enamel is left unaffected.

q11.text: The Old Dominion University explorer is used for
q11.correctAnswer: Exploring the root surface and detecting sub gingival deposits
q11.explanation: The Old Dominion University explorer is a sharp-ended instrument that is used to explore the root surface by tactile sensation in order to study the root anatomy of a tooth. It is used before root planning to detect sub gingival deposits and then afterwards to check that they have been removed. An endodontic explorer is used to locate canal orifices. A William’s probe is used to measure gingival recession and probing depth. Two instrument handles are used to measure mobility of a tooth.

q12.text: Which of the following statements is true for a Fox's plane guide?
q12.correctAnswer: Used to check the parallelism between the incisor’s occlusal plane and interpupillary line

otherAnswers.a1: Used to check the parallelism between the incisor’s occlusal plane and ala-tragal line
otherAnswers.a2: Used to check the parallelism between the posterior occlusal plane and interpupillary line.
otherAnswers.a4: Used to check the parallelism between the ala-tragal line and interpupillary line.

q12.explanation: A Fox’s plane guide is used in the jaw registration stage of denture construction.  First of all, it is used to check that the incisal occlusal plane is parallel with the interpupillary line. It is then used to check that that the posterior occlusal plane is parallel to the ala-tragal line. The Willis Bite Gauge is used to measure resting vertical dimension and the occlusal vertical dimension. Free way space can then be calculated by subtracting the occlusal vertical dimension from the resting vertical dimension.

q13.correctAnswer: Fitting discs for polishing and cutting onto

otherAnswers.a4: Burnish the margins of the restoration

q13.explanation:
Discs that are either screw type or pop on type can be fitted onto mandrels for polishing and cutting restorative materials.  Rose head or round burs are used to cut and remove caries.  Pear and fissure burs are used to shape the cavity preparation.  An enamel chisel, hatchet or gingival margin trimmer can be used to remove unsupported enamel. A burnisher is used to burnish the margins of the restoration.

Scheller-Sheridan, C. (2011) Basic Guide to Dental Instruments. Wiley-Blackwell.

q14.text: An E- type (Epidemiological) BPE probe has
q14.explanation: An E type BPE probe has one band at 3.5-5.5mm. A C – type BPE probe has two bands at 3.5mm and 5.5mm.

q15.text: A slow speed hand piece is used for
q15.correctAnswer: Finishing and polishing restorations and dentinal caries removal
q15.explanation: A slow speed hand piece is used for finishing and polishing restorations and dentinal caries removal. A high-speed hand piece is used for removing enamel, removing existing restorations and gaining access to dentinal caries.

q16.text: A spoon shaped excavator is used for
q16.correctAnswer: Removing dentinal caries from a cavity preparation

otherAnswers.a2: Condensing amalgam into a cavity preparation
otherAnswers.a3: Adapting amalgam to the margins of the restoration
otherAnswers.a4: Carving and shaping correct tooth anatomy into an amalgam preparation

q16.explanation:
A spoon shaped excavator is used to remove dentinal caries from a cavity preparation. An enamel chisel, hatchet or gingival margin trimmer can be used to remove unsupported enamel.  An amalgam plugger/condenser can be used to condense amalgam into a cavity preparation.  A burnisher can be used to adapt amalgam to the margins of the restoration.  An amalgam carver can be used to carve and shape the correct tooth anatomy into an amalgam preparation.

Scheller-Sheridan, C. (2011) Basic Guide to Dental Instruments. Wiley-Blackwell.

q17.text: What is the function of maxillary premolar extraction forceps?
q17.correctAnswer: Extraction of maxillary permanent canines, premolars and anterior deciduous teeth.

otherAnswers.a2: Extraction of maxillary permanent canines and premolars

q17.explanation:
Maxillary premolar extraction forceps are used to extract the maxillary permanent canines, premolars and anterior deciduous teeth.  Maxillary root extraction forceps are used to extract maxillary roots.

Scheller-Sheridan, C. (2011) Basic Guide to Dental Instruments. Wiley-Blackwell.

q18.text: What is the function of Bayonet extraction forceps?
q18.correctAnswer: Extraction of maxillary third molars and roots

otherAnswers.a1: Extraction of maxillary permanent canines, premolars and anterior deciduous teeth.
otherAnswers.a2: Extraction of maxillary anterior permanent teeth
otherAnswers.a3: Extraction of mandibular permanent anterior and premolar teeth

q18.explanation:
Bayonet extraction forceps are used to extract maxillary third molars and roots.  Maxillary premolar extraction forceps are used to extract the maxillary permanent canines, premolars and anterior deciduous teeth. Maxillary straight extraction forceps/ maxillary permanent incisor extraction forceps are used to extract maxillary anterior permanent teeth. Mandibular permanent premolar extraction forceps are used to extract mandibular permanent anterior and premolar teeth. Mandibular root extraction forceps are used to extract mandibular permanent roots.

Scheller-Sheridan, C. (2011) Basic Guide to Dental Instruments. Wiley-Blackwell.

q19.text: Which of the following matrix materials is most commonly used in paedodontics?
q19.explanation:
A T band matrix is most commonly used in paedodontics.  Celluloid strips are clear strips that are used in anterior composite restorations. A stainless steel matrix band is used with a matrix retainer for amalgam restorations. A Hawe supermat matrix is used when proximal walls are replaced temporarily during amalgam and posterior composite restorations. A siqveland matrix retainer is used to hold the matrix material securely.

Scheller-Sheridan, C. (2011) Basic Guide to Dental Instruments. Wiley-Blackwell.

q20.text: The shank of an instrument is
q20.correctAnswer: The part between the handle and working end.

otherAnswers.a1: The functional part of an instrument
otherAnswers.a2: The part of the instrument that the operator grips.
otherAnswers.a3: Provides leverage and stability for the operator

q20.explanation: The shank of an instrument is the part between the handle and working end. The functional part of an instrument is known as the working end. The operator grips the handle of an instrument and this provides stability and leverage. The shank of an instrument can be straight or angled. Scheller-Sheridan, C. (2011) Basic Guide to Dental Instruments. Wiley-Blackwell.

q21.text: Which of the following statements is true of Hedstrom files?
q21.correctAnswer: Must only be used with a push-pull action

otherAnswers.a1: Must only be used with a rotational action
otherAnswers.a2: Can be used with a push pull action or rotational action
otherAnswers.a3: Can be used with a half twist and pull action
otherAnswers.a4: Can be used with a half twist and pull action or push-pull action

q21.explanation: Hedstrom files must only be used with a push-pull action and never rotated.  They are very prone to fracture when twisting actions are used.

q22.text: The root canal reamer is used with a

otherAnswers.a3: Half twist and pull action or push pull action

q22.explanation: The root canal reamers is used with a half twist and pull action.  It has sharp cutting edges that scrape the canal wall as it is worked towards the working length.

q23.text: Which of the following statements is true of a Barbed Broach?
q23.correctAnswer: Removal of intact pulp tissue from wide canals is its main use

otherAnswers.a1: Removal of pulp tissue from very narrow canals is its main use
otherAnswers.a2: Must be engaged tight against the canal wall as it is advanced.

q23.explanation: Barbed broaches are mainly used for the removal of intact pulp tissue from wide canals.  It is a fragile instrument with a high fracture risk. It must be loose in the canal as it is advanced so it can engage soft tissues without fracturing.

q24.text: Which of the following statements is true of Gates Glidden drills?
q24.correctAnswer: Used to enlarge the coronal aspect of root canals

otherAnswers.a1: Used to enlarge the apical third of root canals

q30.correctAnswer: Extend the periphery of an impression tray

Modelling wax is used to record a patient’s jaw relationship. Bite registration paste is used with wax occlusal rims to record a patient’s occlusal relationship. Articulating paper is used to record a patient’s occlusal contacts. Sticky wax is used for denture repairs.

q31.text: What is the equipment of choice to hold shim stock paper with?
q31.explanation: Shim stock paper is a very thin metal film that is used to check occlusal interferences during an occlusal assessment. Due to their minute thickness (roughly 12 um), they should be used with Miller's forceps, as these have long clipping arms that engage the full length of the film. Using your fingers to hold the shim stock film will prove very awkward, as it will stick to the finger due to its electrostatic charge.
